   304	### D. Bare-repo bootstrap — one authoritative owner
   305	
   306	**Owner:** `setup-experiment.sh`. The repo is seeded **before**
   307	`docker compose up` runs, so the seed SHA is known synchronously and
   308	can be written into `.env` for downstream service flags.
   309	
   310	**Mechanism:** setup-experiment runs a one-shot
   311	
   312	```bash
   313	docker compose --env-file <generated-env> run --rm eden-repo-init
   314	```
   315	
   316	against a new `eden-repo-init` service in `compose.yaml`. That
   317	service:
   318	
   319	1. `image:` references the same shared `eden-reference:dev` image
   320	   (so it has Python + the workspace + git available).
   321	2. Mounts only the `eden-bare-repo` named volume at
   322	   `/var/lib/eden/repo`.
   323	3. `command: ["python", "-m", "eden_service_common.repo_init",
   324	   "--repo-path", "/var/lib/eden/repo"]` — a new module that:
   325	   a. If `/var/lib/eden/repo/HEAD` already exists, prints
   326	      `EDEN_REPO_ALREADY_SEEDED sha=<existing-sha>` and exits 0.
   327	   b. Otherwise: runs `git init --bare
   328	      --initial-branch=main`, calls `seed_bare_repo`, prints
   329	      `EDEN_REPO_SEEDED sha=<hex>` to stdout, exits 0.
   330	
   331	The script captures stdout, parses the SHA, and writes it to `.env`
   332	as `EDEN_BASE_COMMIT_SHA=<hex>`. Then the operator runs `docker
   333	compose up`.
   334	
   335	**Crucially:** `eden-repo-init` is **NOT** in any other service's
   336	`depends_on`. It is a setup-time tool, invoked by setup-experiment
   337	via `compose run --rm`, not a `compose up`-time dependency. This
   338	collapses the dual-owner contradiction codex flagged in plan-review
   339	round 0: setup-experiment is the sole owner of repo seeding, and
   340	the seed SHA is known *before* any service starts.
   341	
   342	The compose `profiles:` keyword keeps `eden-repo-init` out of plain
   343	`docker compose up`'s service set:
   344	
   345	```yaml
   346	eden-repo-init:
   347	  profiles: ["setup"]
   348	  ...
   349	```
   350	
   351	`compose run --rm <name>` runs services regardless of profile, so
   352	setup-experiment invokes it normally; plain `compose up` skips it.
   353	
   354	**Re-runnability:** `setup-experiment.sh` is idempotent. Running it
   355	a second time:
   356	
   357	- Re-runs `eden-repo-init`, which short-circuits on the existing
   358	  `HEAD` and re-prints the existing SHA.
   359	- Preserves existing secrets (postgres password, shared token) so
   360	  re-running doesn't rotate them by accident.
   361	- Overwrites `EDEN_PLAN_TASKS` and `experiment-config.yaml`.
   362	
   363	### E. setup-experiment script
   364	
   365	**File:** [`reference/scripts/setup-experiment/setup-experiment.sh`](../../reference/scripts/setup-experiment/setup-experiment.sh)
   366	(plus `README.md`).
   367	
   368	**Why bash, not Python:** the script's job is mostly to (a) read a
   369	YAML field from an existing config, (b) generate a `.env` file from
   370	a template, (c) print human-readable next steps. Bash is the
   371	simplest tool that fits, and it doesn't introduce a "you must `uv
   372	sync` before you can set up an experiment" bootstrap problem.
   373	Python would make the YAML read prettier (vs. `yq` or `python3 -c
   374	"import yaml; …"`), but trades it for the bootstrap requirement.
   375	The bash script will use a one-line `python3 -c` for YAML parsing
   376	since CI's runner has Python — that single dependency stays minor.
   377	
   378	**Inputs:**
   379	
   380	- Required positional arg: path to an experiment config YAML
   381	  (defaults to repo's fixture at
   382	  `tests/fixtures/experiment/.eden/config.yaml`).
   383	- `--experiment-id <id>` (default: derived from config filename
   384	  parent directory).
   385	- `--shared-token <T>` (default: a freshly generated 32-byte hex
   386	  string).
   387	- `--postgres-password <P>` (default: read from existing `.env` if
   388	  present, else freshly generated).
   389	
   390	**Outputs:**
   391	
   392	- `reference/compose/.env` (or `--env-file <path>`) — generated
   393	  Compose env. See section F for the full variable list.
   394	- `reference/compose/experiment-config.yaml` — copy of the input
   395	  config the task-store-server reads at boot via Compose `configs:`.
   396	- Stdout: a short "next steps" message — `docker compose up -d
   397	  --wait`. (**`up -d`, not `restart`** — `restart` does not pick
   398	  up changes to `command:`, env files, or `configs:`. `up -d`
   399	  detects config drift and recreates affected services. See
   400	  https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/compose/up/.)
   401	
   402	**Step ordering** (one-shot, synchronous, no chicken-and-egg):
   403	
   404	1. Generate / preserve secrets. Write a partial `.env` with
   405	   everything except `EDEN_BASE_COMMIT_SHA`.
   406	2. Copy the input config to `reference/compose/experiment-config.yaml`.
   407	3. `docker compose --env-file .env build eden-repo-init` so the
   408	   shared image is available before the next step runs. Build
   409	   output streams to stdout so the operator sees progress.
   410	4. `docker compose --env-file .env run --rm --no-deps eden-repo-init`,
   411	   capture stdout, parse the seed SHA.
   412	   - `--no-deps` keeps future dependency edits from accidentally
   413	     starting Postgres/Gitea/etc. just to seed a repo.
   414	   - The build in step 3 means this never fails on a missing image.
   415	5. Append `EDEN_BASE_COMMIT_SHA=<sha>` to `.env`.
   416	6. Print next-steps message.
   417	
   418	(`docker compose run --build --rm` would collapse 3+4 into one
   419	call, but the explicit two-step keeps build output and seed
   420	output cleanly separated in the operator's terminal — so a
   421	build failure is unambiguous and a seed failure is too.)
   422	
   423	### F. Compose dependency graph
   424	
   425	Final shape (post-setup-experiment):
   426	
   427	```
   428	postgres          → healthy (10a)
   429	gitea             → healthy (10a, idle this chunk)
   430	blob-init         → exited 0 (10a)
   431	eden-repo-init    → exited 0 (new; profile=setup, NOT in `compose up`)
   432	task-store-server → healthy [depends_on: postgres]
   433	orchestrator      → running [depends_on: task-store-server]
   434	planner-host      → running [depends_on: task-store-server]
   435	implementer-host  → running [depends_on: task-store-server]
   436	evaluator-host    → running [depends_on: task-store-server]
   437	web-ui            → healthy [depends_on: task-store-server]
   438	```
   439	
   440	`eden-repo-init` is invoked once by setup-experiment via
   441	`compose run --rm` *before* `compose up`; the bare-repo volume is
   442	already seeded by the time `compose up` starts the long-running
   443	services, so no `compose up`-time dependency on `eden-repo-init` is
   444	needed.
   445	
   446	Worker hosts and orchestrator are long-running clients without HTTP
   447	healthchecks; `compose up --wait` waits on `service_healthy` for
   448	healthcheck-declaring services and `service_started` for the
   449	others. Acceptable for this chunk.
